# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kilometre
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The **25 de Abril Bridge** (Portuguese: *Ponte 25 de Abril*, 25th of April Bridge, Portuguese pronunciation: [ˈpõtɨ ˈvĩtɨ (i) ˈsĩku dɨ ɐˈbɾil]) is a suspension bridge connecting the city of Lisbon, capital of Portugal, with the municipality of Almada on the left (south) bank of the Tagus River.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] It has a main span length of 1,013 metres (3,323 ft; 1.013 km), making it the 48th longest suspension bridge in the world.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] At the time of its inauguration in 1966, the bridge was named **Salazar Bridge** (*Ponte Salazar*), after the Portuguese dictator António de Oliveira Salazar, who ordered its construction.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] After the Carnation Revolution in 1974, which overthrew the remnants of Salazar's *Estado Novo* regime, the bridge was renamed for April 25, the date of the revolution.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] It is also commonly called the **Tagus River Bridge** (in Portuguese: ***Ponte sobre o Tejo***, lit.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Later changes had to be made due to the rapid increase in population.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In the 1990s, a fifth car lane was added, and in 1999, a lower deck, used as a railway track, which was planned since the beginning, was finally built.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Today, the upper deck carries six car lanes while the lower deck carries a double track railway, electrified at 25 kV AC.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] From the late 19th century, there had been proposals to build a bridge across the Tagus.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In 1929, the idea advanced when the Portuguese engineer and entrepreneur, António Bello, requested a government concession for a railway crossing between Lisbon and Montijo (where the Vasco da Gama Bridge, the second bridge serving Lisbon, was later built in 1998).
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] As a result, the Minister of Public Works, Duarte Pacheco, created a commission in 1933 to analyse the request.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The commission reported in 1934, and proposed building a road and rail bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Bids were obtained, but the proposal was subsequently put aside in favor of a bridge crossing the river at Vila Franca de Xira, 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of Lisbon.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In 1953, a new government commission started work and, in 1958, recommended building the bridge, choosing the southern anchor point adjacent to the recently built Christ the King monument (*Cristo-Rei*).
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In 1959, the international invitation to tender for the project received four bids.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In 1960, the winner was announced as a consortium headed by the United States Steel Export Company, which had also submitted a bid in 1935.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The American School of Lisbon was founded largely to educate the children of the American engineers brought to Portugal to work on the construction of the bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Forty-five months later, six months ahead of schedule, the bridge was inaugurated on 6 August 1966.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Presiding at the ceremony was the President of Portugal, Admiral Américo Thomaz.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Also present were the Prime-Minister, António de Oliveira Salazar, and the Patriarch of Lisbon, Cardinal Manuel Gonçalves Cerejeira.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The bridge was named Salazar Bridge (*Ponte Salazar*), after Prime Minister Salazar.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] United States Steel International Inc., based in New York, was prime contractor for the bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Morrison-Knudsen of Portugal Ltd., an American firm based in Boise, Idaho, was U.S.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Morrison-Knudsen had previously worked on the San Francisco Bay Bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The bridge was designed by Steinman, Boynton, Gronquist and London of New York, and Tudor Engineering Company of San Francisco.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Four workers died, out of a total of 3,000 who worked on the site.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Construction took a total of 2,185,000 man-hours of work.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The total cost of the bridge came to 2.2 billion Portuguese escudos, or US$32 million (US$225 million in 2011 adjusted for inflation).
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Soon after the Carnation Revolution in 1974, the bridge was renamed the "25 de Abril Bridge", the day the revolution had occurred.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] A symbol of those times was captured on film, with citizens removing the large brass letters spelling "Salazar" from one of the main pillars of the bridge and painting a provisional "25 de Abril" in its place.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The upper platform, running 70 m (230 ft) above water, had four car lanes, two in each direction, with a dividing guardrail.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] On 23 July 1990, the guardrail was removed and a fifth, reversible lane was created.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] On 6 November 1998, the side walls were extended and reinforced to make space for the present six lanes.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Cars crossing the bridge make a peculiar hum - listen (59s) - because the two inner lanes are made of metallic grating rather than asphalt to minimize aerodynamic forces by means of pressure equalization.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Since 30 June 1999, the lower platform has carried a double track railway.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] To accommodate that, the bridge underwent extensive structural reinforcements, including a second set of main cables, placed above the original set, and the main towers were increased in height.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The railway had been part of the initial design, but was eliminated for economy, so the initial structure was lightened.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The original builder American Bridge Company was called again for the job, performing the first aerial spinning of additional main cables on a loaded, fully operational suspension bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Traffic soon increased well beyond predictions, and has remained at maximum capacity despite the enlargement from four to six lanes, the addition of the railway, and the building of a second bridge serving Lisbon, the Vasco da Gama Bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] A third bridge has been on and off government plans for some time, but in May 2024 the government announced to prioritize building this new bridge as part of the new Lisbon-Madrid high-speed rail line, to be finalized in 2034.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Normally, pedestrians cannot walk across the bridge, but every year there is a half-marathon that starts on the south bank and finishes in the north bank (Belem).
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In September 2017, an observation deck was built allowing people to go to the platform.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Using the bridge has always incurred a toll, first in both directions and then, from 1993, while travelling northbound only.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The toll plaza situated on the south bank of the Tagus River.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The tolls have become a source of political dispute in recent years.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The bridge was projected to have paid all debt in 20 years, and to become toll-free (or have a reduced toll) after that period.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] However, the Government kept charging tolls well beyond the 20-year period, until it gave the concession to Lusoponte, creating a monopoly of the Tagus crossing in Lisbon.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] When opened, people had to park their car and walk to buy a toll ticket costing 20 escudos.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] On 14 June 1994, the government, which ran the bridge at the time, raised the toll by 50%, from 100 to 150 escudos, to prepare to give the bridge into private concession for 40 years from 1 January 1996.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The concessionaire was Lusoponte, a private consortium formed to build the Vasco da Gama Bridge at no cost to the public finances in exchange for tolls from both bridges.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] As a result, a popular uprising led to road blockades of the bridge and consequent police charges, an event which made the right-wing Government highly unpopular and which many believe led to a centre-left win in the 1995 general elections.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The toll is set at €2.15 for passenger cars (as of September 2025), northbound (into Lisbon).
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] There is no toll southbound, and until 2010, no tolls were collected during the month of August.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] From 2011 on, the Portuguese Government abolished that exception, in order to help the efforts to reduce the budget deficit.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Assuming that no legal changes happen, the concession will end on 24 March 2030, after which the bridge will again be state-managed.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The 25 de Abril Bridge is based in part on two San Francisco Bay Area bridges.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Its paint is the same International Orange color as the famous Golden Gate Bridge, and the design is similar as well to the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Both the Bay Bridge and the 25 de Abril Bridge were built by the same company.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] The American Society of Civil Engineers says: "Like its sister bridge, the SFOBB in San Francisco, the Tagus River Bridge is located in an area with a long history of earthquakes" and seismic data had to be taken into account in its construction.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Another sister bridge is the Forth Road Bridge in Edinburgh.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Upon completion, the bridge had the longest suspended span and the longest main span in Continental Europe, the world's longest continuous truss, and the world's deepest bridge foundation.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] It was the fifth-longest suspension bridge in the world, and the longest outside the US.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] As of 2006, a daily average of 150,000 cars cross the bridge, including 7,000 during the peak hour.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] Rail traffic is also heavy, with a daily average of 157 trains.
[src:kilometre/25-de-abril-bridge] In all, around 380,000 people cross the bridge daily.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Varieties of American English include many patterns of pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and particularly spelling that are unified nationwide but distinct from other forms of English around the world.
[src:kilometre/american-english] However, historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single mainstream American accent.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents having emerged in the 20th century.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The use of English in the United States is a result of British colonization of the Americas.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the early 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:kilometre/american-english] English thus predominated in the colonies even by the end of the 17th century's first immigration of non-English speakers from Western Europe and Africa.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Firsthand descriptions of a fairly uniform American English (particularly in contrast to the diverse regional dialects of British English) became common after the mid-18th century, while at the same time speakers' identification with this new variety increased.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Since the 18th century, American English has developed into some new varieties, including regional dialects that retain minor influences from waves of immigrant speakers of diverse languages, primarily European languages.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Some racial and regional variation in American English reflects these groups' patterns of geographic settlement, segregation, and resettlement.
[src:kilometre/american-english] This can be seen, for example, in the influence of 18th-century Protestant Ulster Scots immigrants (known in the U.S. as the Scotch-Irish) in Appalachia developing Appalachian English and the 20th-century Great Migration bringing African-American Vernacular English to the Great Lakes urban centers.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Most American English accents fall under an umbrella known as General American.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Rather than one particular accent, General American is a spectrum of those American accents that Americans themselves do not associate with some particular region, ethnicity, or socioeconomic group.
[src:kilometre/american-english] General American features are used most by Americans in formal contexts or who are highly educated.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Regional accents whose native features are perceived as General American include the accents of the North Midland (parts of the Midwest), Western New England, and the West.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The General American sound system's scope of influence and degree of expansion has been debated by linguists since the term was first used roughly a century ago.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Many late-20th and early-21st century studies are showing that it is gradually ousting the regional accents in urban areas of the South and the interior North, New York City, Philadelphia, and many other areas.
[src:kilometre/american-english] It can generally be said that younger Americans are avoiding their traditional local features in favor of this more nationwide norm.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Furthermore, even General American itself appears to be evolving, with linguists identifying new features in speakers born since the last quarter of the 20th century, like a merger of the low-back vowels and a potentially related vowel shift, that are spreading across the nation.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Like many British accents, T glottalization is the norm in American accents, though only in particular environments (with *satin* pronounced [ˈsæʔn̩], not [ˈsætn̩]).
[src:kilometre/american-english] Specifically, the LOT–PALM merger is complete among most Americans and the LOT–THOUGHT merger among roughly half.
[src:kilometre/american-english] A three-way LOT–PALM–THOUGHT merger is also very common, meaning that words like *baht*, *bot*, and *bought* are all homophones.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Most Americans pronounce the diphthong /aɪ/ before a voiceless consonant different from that same vowel before a voiced consonant: thus, in *price* and *bright* versus in *prize* and *bride*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] For many, outside the South, the first element of the diphthong is a higher and shorter vowel sound when in pre-voiceless position as opposed to pre-voiced position.
[src:kilometre/american-english] All of these phenomena are explained in further detail under General American.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Unlike American accents, the traditional standard accent of (southern) England has evolved a *trap–bath* split.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Moreover, American accents preserve /h/ at the start of syllables, while perhaps a majority of the regional dialects of England participate in /h/ dropping, particularly in informal contexts.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The process of developing new lexical items began as soon as British English-speaking colonists in North America began borrowing names for unfamiliar flora, fauna, and topography from the Native American languages.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Examples of such names are *opossum, raccoon, squash*, *moose* (from Algonquian), *wigwam*, and *moccasin*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] American English speakers have integrated traditionally non-English terms and expressions into the mainstream cultural lexicon; for instance, *en masse*, from French; *cookie*, from Dutch; *kindergarten* from German, and *rodeo* from Spanish.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Landscape features are often loanwords from French or Spanish, and the word *corn*, used in England to refer to wheat (or any cereal), came to denote the maize plant, the most important crop in the U.S.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Other common differences between UK and American English include: *aerial* (UK) vs.
[src:kilometre/american-english] *apartment*, *fringe* (UK; for hair hanging over the forehead) vs.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Most Mexican Spanish contributions came after the War of 1812, with the opening of the West, like *ranch* (now a common house style).
[src:kilometre/american-english] Due to Mexican culinary influence, many Spanish words are incorporated in general use when talking about certain popular dishes: cilantro (instead of coriander), queso, tacos, quesadillas, enchiladas, tostadas, fajitas, burritos, and guacamole.
[src:kilometre/american-english] These words usually lack an English equivalent and are found in popular restaurants.
[src:kilometre/american-english] New forms of dwelling created new terms *(lot, waterfront)* and types of homes like *log cabin, adobe* in the 18th century; *apartment, shanty* in the 19th century; *project, condominium, townhouse, mobile home* in the 20th century; and parts thereof *(driveway, breezeway, backyard)*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Already existing English words—such as *store, shop, lumber*—underwent shifts in meaning; others remained in the U.S. while changing in Britain.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Science, urbanization, and democracy have been important factors in bringing about changes in the written and spoken language of the United States.
[src:kilometre/american-english] From the world of business and finance came new terms (*merger, downsize, bottom line*), from sports and gambling terminology came, specific jargon aside, common everyday American idioms, including many idioms related to baseball.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The names of some American inventions remained largely confined to North America (*elevator* [except in the aeronautical sense], *gasoline*) as did certain automotive terms (*truck*, *trunk*).
[src:kilometre/american-english] New foreign loanwords came with 19th and early 20th century European immigration to the U.S.; notably, from Yiddish *(chutzpah, schmooze, bupkis, glitch*) and German (*hamburger, wiener*).
[src:kilometre/american-english] American English has always shown a marked tendency to use words in different parts of speech and nouns are often used as verbs.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Examples of nouns that are now also verbs are *interview, advocate, vacuum, lobby, pressure, rear-end, transition, feature, profile, hashtag, head, divorce, loan, estimate, X-ray, spearhead, skyrocket, showcase, bad-mouth, vacation, major,* and many others.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance *foothill, landslide* (in all senses), *backdrop, teenager,* *brainstorm, bandwagon, hitchhike, smalltime,* and a huge number of others.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Other compound words have been founded based on industrialization and the wave of the automobile: five-passenger car, four-door sedan, two-door sedan, and station-wagon (called an estate car in British English).
[src:kilometre/american-english] Some are euphemistic *(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).* Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: *stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,* and many more.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (*win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to* and many others).
[src:kilometre/american-english] Noun endings such as *-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)* and *-cian (beautician)* are also particularly productive in the U.S.
[src:kilometre/american-english] A number of words and meanings that originated in Middle English or Early Modern English and that have been in everyday use in the United States have since disappeared in most varieties of British English; some of these have cognates in Lowland Scots.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Terms such as *fall* ("autumn"), *faucet* ("tap"), *diaper* ("nappy"; itself unused in the U.S.), *candy* ("sweets"), *skillet*, *eyeglasses*, and *obligate* are often regarded as Americanisms.
[src:kilometre/american-english] *Fall*, however, came to denote the season in 16th century England, a contraction of Middle English expressions like "fall of the leaf" and "fall of the year".
[src:kilometre/american-english] *Gotten* (past participle of *get*) is often considered to be largely an Americanism.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Other words and meanings were brought back to Britain from the U.S., especially in the second half of the 20th century; these include *hire* ("to employ"), *I guess* (famously criticized by H.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Fowler), *baggage*, *hit* (a place), and the adverbs *overly* and *presently* ("currently").
[src:kilometre/american-english] Some of these, for example, *monkey wrench* and *wastebasket*, originated in 19th century Britain.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The adjectives *mad* meaning "angry", *smart* meaning "intelligent", and *sick* meaning "ill" are also more frequent in American (and Irish) English than British English.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Linguist Bert Vaux created a survey, completed in 2003, polling English speakers across the United States about their specific everyday word choices, hoping to identify regionalisms.
[src:kilometre/american-english] American English and British English (BrE) differ in relatively minor ways in their grammar and writing conventions.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The first large American dictionary, *An American Dictionary of the English Language*, known as Webster's Dictionary, was written by Noah Webster in 1828, codifying several of these spellings.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Often, these differences are a matter of relative preferences rather than absolute rules; and most are not stable since the two varieties are constantly influencing each other, and American English is not a standardized set of dialects.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Differences in orthography are also minor.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The main differences are that American English usually uses spellings such as *flavor* for British *flavour*, *fiber* for *fibre*, *defense* for *defence*, *analyze* for *analyse*, *license* for *licence*, *catalog* for *catalogue* and *traveling* for *travelling*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Noah Webster popularized such spellings in America, but he did not invent most of them.
[src:kilometre/american-english] AmE almost always uses *-ize* in words like *realize*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] BrE prefers *-ise*, but also uses *-ize* on occasion (see: Oxford spelling).
[src:kilometre/american-english] There are a few differences in punctuation rules.
[src:kilometre/american-english] British English is more tolerant of run-on sentences, called "comma splices" in American English, and American English prefers that periods and commas be placed inside closing quotation marks even in cases in which British rules would place them outside.
[src:kilometre/american-english] American English also favors the double quotation mark ("like this") over the single ('as here').
[src:kilometre/american-english] AmE sometimes favors words that are morphologically more complex, whereas BrE uses clipped forms, such as AmE *transportation* and BrE *transport* or where the British form is a back-formation, such as AmE *burglarize* and BrE *burgle* (from *burglar*).
[src:kilometre/american-english] However, while individuals usually use one or the other, both forms will be widely understood and mostly used alongside each other within the two systems.
[src:kilometre/american-english] as well as the related Telsur Project's regional maps.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Any region may also contain speakers of a "General American" accent that resists the marked features of their region.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and leveling, while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.
[src:kilometre/american-english] As of the 20th century, the middle and eastern Great Lakes area, Chicago being the largest city with these speakers, also ushered in certain unique features, including the fronting of the LOT /ɑ/ vowel in the mouth toward [a] and tensing of the TRAP /æ/ vowel wholesale to [eə].
[src:kilometre/american-english] These sound changes have triggered a series of other vowel shifts in the same region, known by linguists as the "Inland North".
[src:kilometre/american-english] The Inland North shares with the Eastern New England dialect (including Boston accents) a backer tongue positioning of the GOOSE /u/ vowel (to [u]) and the MOUTH /aʊ/ vowel (to [ɑʊ~äʊ]) in comparison to the rest of the country.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Ranging from northern New England across the Great Lakes to Minnesota, another Northern regional marker is the variable fronting of /ɑ/ before /r/, for example, appearing four times in the stereotypical Boston shibboleth *Park the car in Harvard Yard*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Several other phenomena serve to distinguish regional American accents.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Boston, Pittsburgh, Upper Midwestern, and Western U.S. accents have fully completed a merger of the LOT vowel with the THOUGHT vowel (/ɑ/ and /ɔ/, respectively): a *cot–caught* merger, which is rapidly spreading throughout the whole country.
[src:kilometre/american-english] However, the South, Inland North, and a Northeastern coastal corridor passing through Rhode Island, New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore typically preserve an older *cot–caught* distinction.
[src:kilometre/american-english] For that Northeastern corridor, the realization of the THOUGHT vowel is particularly marked, as depicted in humorous spellings, like in *tawk* and *cawfee* (*talk* and *coffee*), which intend to represent it being tense and diphthongal: [oə].
[src:kilometre/american-english] A split of TRAP into two separate phonemes, using different *a* pronunciations for example in *gap* [æ] versus *gas* [eə], further defines New York City as well as Philadelphia–Baltimore accents.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Most Americans preserve all historical /r/ sounds, using what is known as a rhotic accent.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Non-rhoticity makes a word like *car* sound like *cah* or *source* like *sauce*.
[src:kilometre/american-english] New York City and Southern accents are the most widely recognized regional accents in the country, as well as the most stigmatized and socially disfavored.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The fronting of the vowels of GOOSE, GOAT, MOUTH, and STRUT tends to also define Southern accents as well as the accents spoken in the "Midland": a vast band of the country that constitutes an intermediate dialect region between the traditional North and South.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Western U.S. accents mostly fall under the General American spectrum.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Although no longer region-specific, African-American Vernacular English, which remains the native variety of most working- and middle-class African Americans, has a close relationship to Southern dialects and has greatly influenced everyday speech of many Americans, including hip hop culture.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Hispanic and Latino Americans have also developed native-speaker varieties of English.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The best-studied Latino Englishes are Chicano English, spoken in the West and Midwest, and New York Latino English, spoken in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Additionally, ethnic varieties such as Yeshiva English and "Yinglish" are spoken by some American Orthodox Jews, Cajun Vernacular English by some Cajuns in southern Louisiana, and Pennsylvania Dutch English by some Pennsylvania Dutch people.
[src:kilometre/american-english] American Indian Englishes have been documented among diverse Indian tribes.
[src:kilometre/american-english] The island state of Hawaii, though primarily English-speaking, is also home to a creole language known commonly as Hawaiian Pidgin, and some Hawaii residents speak English with a Pidgin-influenced accent.
[src:kilometre/american-english] In 2024, about 247.7 million Americans, aged five or above, spoke English at home, a majority (77%) of the total U.S. population aged five and over.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Of the 50 states, 32 have adopted legislation granting official (or co-official) status to English within their jurisdictions, in some cases as part of what has been called the English-only movement.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Typically only "English" is specified, not a particular variety like American English.
[src:kilometre/american-english] Puerto Rico is the only United States territory in which another language – Spanish – is the common language at home, in public, and in government.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Historically, the astronomical unit was conceived as the average Earth-Sun distance (the average of Earth's aphelion and perihelion), before its modern redefinition in 2012.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The astronomical unit is used primarily for measuring distances within the Solar System or around other stars.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] It is also a fundamental component in the definition of another unit of astronomical length, the parsec.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] One au is approximately equivalent to 499 light-seconds.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] A variety of unit symbols and abbreviations have been in use for the astronomical unit.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In a 1976 resolution, the International Astronomical Union (IAU) had used the symbol *A* to denote a length equal to the astronomical unit.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In the astronomical literature, the symbol AU is common.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In 2006, the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) had recommended ua as the symbol for the unit, from the French "unité astronomique".
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In the non-normative Annex C to ISO 80000-3:2006 (later withdrawn), the symbol of the astronomical unit was also ua.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In 2012, the IAU, noting "that various symbols are presently in use for the astronomical unit", recommended the use of the symbol "au".
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The scientific journals published by the American Astronomical Society and the Royal Astronomical Society subsequently adopted this symbol.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In the 2014 revision and 2019 edition of the SI Brochure, the BIPM used the unit symbol "au".
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Earth's orbit around the Sun is an ellipse.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The semi-major axis of this elliptic orbit is defined to be half of the straight line segment that joins the perihelion and aphelion.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The centre of the Sun lies on this straight line segment, but not at its midpoint.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Because ellipses are well-understood shapes, measuring the points of its extremes defined the exact shape mathematically, and made possible calculations for the entire orbit as well as predictions based on observation.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In addition, it mapped out exactly the largest straight-line distance that Earth traverses over the course of a year, defining times and places for observing the largest parallax (apparent shifts of position) in nearby stars.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Knowing Earth's shift and a star's shift enabled the star's distance to be calculated.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] But all measurements are subject to some degree of error or uncertainty, and the uncertainties in the length of the astronomical unit only increased uncertainties in the stellar distances.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Improvements in precision have always been a key to improving astronomical understanding.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Throughout the twentieth century, measurements became increasingly precise and sophisticated, and ever more dependent on accurate observation of the effects described by Einstein's theory of relativity and upon the mathematical tools it used.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Improving measurements were continually checked and cross-checked by means of improved understanding of the laws of celestial mechanics, which govern the motions of objects in space.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The expected positions and distances of objects at an established time are calculated (in au) from these laws, and assembled into a collection of data called an ephemeris.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory HORIZONS System provides one of several ephemeris computation services.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In 1976, to establish a more precise measure for the astronomical unit, the IAU formally adopted a new definition.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Although directly based on the then-best available observational measurements, the definition was recast in terms of the then-best mathematical derivations from celestial mechanics and planetary ephemerides.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] It stated that "the astronomical unit of length is that length (*A*) for which the Gaussian gravitational constant (*k*) takes the value 0.01720209895 when the units of measurement are the astronomical units of length, mass and time".
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Subsequent explorations of the Solar System by space probes made it possible to obtain precise measurements of the relative positions of the inner planets and other objects by means of radar and telemetry.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] As with all radar measurements, these rely on measuring the time taken for photons to be reflected from an object.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Because all photons move at the speed of light in vacuum, a fundamental constant of the universe, the distance of an object from the probe is calculated as the product of the speed of light and the measured time.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] However, for precision the calculations require adjustment for things such as the motions of the probe and object while the photons are transiting.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In addition, the measurement of the time itself must be translated to a standard scale that accounts for relativistic time dilation.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Comparison of the ephemeris positions with time measurements expressed in Barycentric Dynamical Time (TDB) leads to a value for the speed of light in astronomical units per day (of 86400 s).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In 1983, the BIPM modified the International System of Units (SI) to make the metre defined as the distance travelled in a vacuum by light in 1 / 299792458 s.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] This replaced the previous definition, valid between 1960 and 1983, which was that the metre equalled a certain number of wavelengths of a certain emission line of krypton-86.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] (The reason for the change was an improved method of measuring the speed of light.) The speed of light could then be expressed exactly as *c*0 = 299792458 m/s, a standard also adopted by the IERS numerical standards.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] From this definition and the 2009 IAU standard, the time for light to traverse an astronomical unit is found to be *τ*A = 499.0047838061±0.00000001 s, which is slightly more than 8 minutes 19 seconds.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] By multiplication, the best IAU 2009 estimate was *A* = *c*0*τ*A = 149597870700±3 m, based on a comparison of Jet Propulsion Laboratory and IAA–RAS ephemerides.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In the 2014 revision of the SI Brochure, the BIPM recognised the IAU's 2012 redefinition of the astronomical unit as 149597870700 m.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] This estimate was still derived from observation and measurements subject to error, and based on techniques that did not yet standardize all relativistic effects, and thus were not constant for all observers.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In 2012, finding that the equalization of relativity alone would make the definition overly complex, the IAU simply used the 2009 estimate to redefine the astronomical unit as a conventional unit of length directly tied to the metre (exactly 149597870700 m).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The new definition recognizes as a consequence that the astronomical unit has reduced importance, limited in use to a convenience in some applications.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] With the definitions used before 2012, the astronomical unit was dependent on the heliocentric gravitational constant, that is the product of the gravitational constant, *G*, and the solar mass, *M*☉.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Neither *G* nor *M*☉ can be measured to high accuracy separately, but the value of their product is known very precisely from observing the relative positions of planets (Kepler's third law expressed in terms of Newtonian gravitation).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Only the product is required to calculate planetary positions for an ephemeris, so ephemerides are calculated in astronomical units and not in SI units.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The calculation of ephemerides also requires a consideration of the effects of general relativity.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] This is because the distance between Earth and the Sun is not fixed (it varies between 0.9832898912 and 1.0167103335 au) and, when Earth is closer to the Sun (perihelion), the Sun's gravitational field is stronger and Earth is moving faster along its orbital path.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] As the metre is defined in terms of the second and the speed of light is constant for all observers, the terrestrial metre appears to change in length compared with the "planetary metre" on a periodic basis.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The metre is defined to be a unit of proper length.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Indeed, the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) notes that "its definition applies only within a spatial extent sufficiently small that the effects of the non-uniformity of the gravitational field can be ignored".
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] As such, a distance within the Solar System without specifying the frame of reference for the measurement is problematic.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The astronomical unit is typically used for stellar system scale distances, such as the size of a protostellar disk or the heliocentric distance (distance from the Sun's centre) of an asteroid, whereas other units are used for other distances in astronomy.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The astronomical unit is too small to be convenient for interstellar distances, where the parsec and light-year are widely used.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The parsec (parallax arcsecond) is defined in terms of the astronomical unit, being the distance of an object with a parallax of 1″.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The light-year is often used in popular works, but is not an approved non-SI unit and is rarely used by professional astronomers.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] When simulating a numerical model of the Solar System, the astronomical unit provides an appropriate scale that minimizes (overflow, underflow and truncation) errors in floating point calculations.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Many early measurements of the Earth-Sun distance are wildly incorrect, primarily because the measurements rely on the ratio of the diameter of the Earth to the distance of the Sun.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Since this ratio is 1/12000, small errors in the size of the Earth lead to large errors in the Earth-Sun distance.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Around 280 BCE, Aristarchus carefully measured the Moon-Earth-Sun angle when the Moon is in its first quarter and used this to estimate the distance to the Sun.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The exact timing and angle measurement are essential.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] He estimated the angle at as 87° (the true value being close to 89.853°) and reported in *On the Sizes and Distances of the Sun and Moon* the distance to the Sun is 18 to 20 times the distance to the Moon, whereas the true ratio is about 389.174.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Depending on the distance that Aristarchus used for the distance to the Moon, his calculated distance to the Sun would fall between 380 and 1520 Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Hipparchus gave an estimate of the distance of Earth from the Sun, quoted by Pappus as equal to 490 Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] According to the conjectural reconstructions of Noel Swerdlow and G.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Toomer, this was derived from his assumption of a "least perceptible" solar parallax of 7′.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] A Chinese mathematical treatise, the *Zhoubi Suanjing* (c.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] 1st century BCE), shows how the distance to the Sun can be computed geometrically, using the different lengths of the noontime shadows observed at three places 1000 *li* apart and the assumption that Earth is flat.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] In the 2nd century CE, Ptolemy estimated the mean distance of the Sun as 1210 times Earth's radius.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] To determine this value, Ptolemy started by measuring the Moon's parallax, finding what amounted to a horizontal lunar parallax of 1° 26′, which was much too large.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] He then derived a maximum lunar distance of ⁠64+1/6⁠ Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Because of cancelling errors in his parallax figure, his theory of the Moon's orbit, and other factors, this figure was approximately correct.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Given these data, the distance of the Sun from Earth can be trigonometrically computed to be 1210 Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] This gives a ratio of solar to lunar distance of approximately 19, matching Aristarchus's figure.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Although Ptolemy's procedure is theoretically workable, it is very sensitive to small changes in the data, so much so that changing a measurement by a few per cent can make the solar distance infinite.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] After Greek astronomy was transmitted to the medieval Islamic world, astronomers made some changes to Ptolemy's cosmological model, but did not greatly change his estimate of the Earth–Sun distance.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] For example, in his introduction to Ptolemaic astronomy, al-Farghānī gave a mean solar distance of 1170 Earth radii, whereas in his *zij*, al-Battānī used a mean solar distance of 1108 Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Subsequent astronomers, such as al-Bīrūnī, used similar values.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Later in Europe, Copernicus and Tycho Brahe also used comparable figures (1142 and 1150 Earth radii), and so Ptolemy's approximate Earth–Sun distance survived through the 16th century.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] By the 17th century the problems with the measurement techniques came to be understood.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Johannes Kepler was the first to realize that Ptolemy's estimate must be significantly too low (according to Kepler, at least by a factor of three) in his *Rudolphine Tables* (1627).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Kepler's laws of planetary motion allowed astronomers to calculate the relative distances of the planets from the Sun, and rekindled interest in measuring the absolute value for Earth (which could then be applied to the other planets).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The invention of the telescope allowed far more accurate measurements of angles than is possible with the naked eye.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Flemish astronomer Godefroy Wendelin repeated Aristarchus’ measurements in 1635, and found that Ptolemy's value was too low by a factor of at least eleven.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] A somewhat more accurate estimate can be obtained by observing the transit of Venus.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] By measuring the transit in two different locations, one can accurately calculate the parallax of Venus and from the relative distance of Earth and Venus from the Sun, the solar parallax α (which cannot be measured directly due to the brightness of the Sun).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Jeremiah Horrocks had attempted to produce an estimate based on his observation of the 1639 transit (published in 1662), giving a solar parallax of 15″, similar to Wendelin's figure.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The smaller the solar parallax, the greater the distance between the Sun and Earth: a solar parallax of 15″ is equivalent to an Earth–Sun distance of 13750 Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Christiaan Huygens believed that the distance was even greater: by comparing the apparent sizes of Venus and Mars, he estimated a value of about 24000 Earth radii, equivalent to a solar parallax of 8.6″.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Jean Richer and Giovanni Domenico Cassini measured the parallax of Mars between Paris and Cayenne in French Guiana when Mars was at its closest to Earth in 1672.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] They arrived at a figure for the solar parallax of 9.5″, equivalent to an Earth–Sun distance of about 22000 Earth radii.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] They were also the first astronomers to have access to an accurate and reliable value for the radius of Earth, which had been measured by their colleague Jean Picard in 1669 as 3269000 *toises*.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] This same year saw another estimate for the astronomical unit by John Flamsteed, which accomplished it alone by measuring the martian diurnal parallax.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Another colleague, Ole Rømer, discovered the finite speed of light in 1676: the speed was so great that it was usually quoted as the time required for light to travel from the Sun to the Earth, or "light time per unit distance", a convention that is still followed by astronomers today.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] A better method for observing Venus transits was devised by James Gregory and published in his *Optica Promata* (1663).
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] It was strongly advocated by Edmond Halley and was applied to the transits of Venus observed in 1761 and 1769, and then again in 1874 and 1882.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Transits of Venus occur in pairs, but less than one pair every century, and observing the transits in 1761 and 1769 was an unprecedented international scientific operation including observations by James Cook and Charles Green from Tahiti.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Despite the Seven Years' War, dozens of astronomers were dispatched to observing points around the world at great expense and personal danger: several of them died in the endeavour.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The various results were collated by Jérôme Lalande to give a figure for the solar parallax of 8.6″.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Karl Rudolph Powalky had made an estimate of 8.83″ in 1864.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Another method involved determining the constant of aberration.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Simon Newcomb gave great weight to this method when deriving his widely accepted value of 8.80″ for the solar parallax (close to the modern value of 8.794143″), although Newcomb also used data from the transits of Venus.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Michelson to measure the speed of light with Earth-based equipment; combined with the constant of aberration (which is related to the light time per unit distance), this gave the first direct measurement of the Earth–Sun distance in metres.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Newcomb's value for the solar parallax (and for the constant of aberration and the Gaussian gravitational constant) were incorporated into the first international system of astronomical constants in 1896, which remained in place for the calculation of ephemerides until 1964.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The name "astronomical unit" was first used in 1848.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The discovery of the near-Earth asteroid 433 Eros and its passage near Earth in 1900–1901 allowed a considerable improvement in parallax measurement.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Another international project to measure the parallax of 433 Eros was undertaken in 1930–1931.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Direct radar measurements of the distances to Venus and Mars became available in the early 1960s.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Along with improved measurements of the speed of light, these showed that Newcomb's values for the solar parallax and the constant of aberration were inconsistent with one another.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] where G is the Newtonian constant of gravitation, *M*☉ is the solar mass, k is the numerical value of Gaussian gravitational constant and D is the time period of one day.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The Sun is constantly losing mass by radiating away energy, so the orbits of the planets are steadily expanding outward from the Sun.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] This has led to calls to abandon the astronomical unit as a unit of measurement.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] As the speed of light has an exact defined value in SI units and the Gaussian gravitational constant k is fixed in the astronomical system of units, measuring the light time per unit distance is exactly equivalent to measuring the product G×*M*☉ in SI units.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Hence, it is possible to construct ephemerides entirely in SI units, which is increasingly becoming the norm.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] A 2004 analysis of radiometric measurements in the inner Solar System suggested that the secular increase in the unit distance was much larger than can be accounted for by solar radiation, +15±4 metres per century.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The measurements of the secular variations of the astronomical unit are not confirmed by other authors and are quite controversial.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Furthermore, since 2010, the astronomical unit has not been estimated by the planetary ephemerides.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] The following table contains some distances given in astronomical units.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] It includes some examples with distances that are normally not given in astronomical units, because they are either too short or far too long.
[src:kilometre/astronomical-unit] Examples are listed by increasing distance.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The following are examples of orders of magnitude for different lengths.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, the following list describes various lengths between $1.6\times 10^{-35}$ metres and $10^{10^{10^{122}}}$ metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] Metres are used in these tables to provide a common reference point, but metric prefixes above "k" are not commonly used with metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] So for example, 1.21 Gm would more commonly be written as 1.21 million km or (in scientific notation) 1.21 × 106 km.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] Interplanetary distances are also commonly measured in astronomical units.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] Distances on the interstellar or larger scale are typically measured in light-years or parsecs.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *quectometre* (SI symbol: *qm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−30 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths shorter than 10−30 m (1 qm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *rontometre* (SI symbol: *rm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−27 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *yoctometre* (SI symbol: *ym*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−24 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *zeptometre* (SI symbol: *zm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−21 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−21 m and 10−20 m (1 zm and 10 zm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−20 m and 10−19 m (10 zm and 100 zm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−19 m and 10−18 m (100 zm and 1 am).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *attometre* (SI symbol: *am*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−18 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−18 m and 10−17 m (1 am and 10 am).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−17 m and 10−16 m (10 am and 100 am).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−16 m and 10−15 m (100 am and 1 fm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *femtometre* (SI symbol: *fm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−15 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] In particle physics, this unit is sometimes called a fermi, also with abbreviation "fm".
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−15 metres and 10−14 metres (1 femtometre and 10 fm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−14 m and 10−13 m (10 fm and 100 fm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−13 m and 10−12 m (100 fm and 1 pm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude this section lists lengths between 10−12 and 10−11 m (1 pm and 10 pm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude this section lists lengths between 10−11 and 10−10 m (10 pm and 100 pm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude this section lists lengths between 10−10 and 10−9 m (100 pm and 1 nm; 1 Å and 10 Å).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−9 and 10−8 m (1 nm and 10 nm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude this section lists lengths between 10−8 and 10−7 m (10 nm and 100 nm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−7 and 10−6 m (100 nm and 1 μm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *micrometre* (SI symbol: *μm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−6 metres (⁠1/1000000⁠ m = 0.000001 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists some items with lengths between 10−6 and 10−5 m (between 1 and 10 micrometres, or μm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−5 m and 10−4 m (10 μm and 100 μm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−4 m and 10−3 m (100 μm and 1 mm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The term *myriometre* (abbr. mom, equivalent to 100 micrometres; frequently confused with the *myriametre*, 10 kilometres) is deprecated; the decimal metric prefix myrio- is obsolete and was not included among the prefixes when the International System of Units was introduced in 1960.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *millimetre* (SI symbol: *mm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−3 metres (⁠1/1000⁠ m = 0.001 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−3 m and 10−2 m (1 mm and 1 cm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *centimetre* (SI symbol: *cm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−2 metres (⁠1/100⁠ m = 0.01 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10−2 m and 10−1 m (1 cm and 1 dm).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *decimetre* (SI symbol: *dm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10−1 metres (⁠1/10⁠ m = 0.1 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10 centimetres and 100 centimetres (10−1 metre and 1 metre).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between one metre and ten metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] The *decametre* (SI symbol: *dam*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 10 metres (101 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p01] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10 and 100 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *hectometre* (SI symbol: *hm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 100 metres (102 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To compare different orders of magnitude this section lists lengths between 100 metres and 1,000 metres (1 kilometre).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *kilometre* (SI symbol: *km*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1000 metres (103 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 1 kilometre and 10 kilometres (103 and 104 metres).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 10 and 100 kilometres (104 to 105 metres).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *myriametre* (sometimes also spelled *myriometre*; 10,000 metres) is a deprecated unit name; the decimal metric prefix myria- (sometimes also written as myrio-) is obsolete and was not included among the prefixes when the International System of Units was introduced in 1960.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] A length of *100 kilometres* (about 62 miles), as a rough amount, is relatively common in measurements on Earth and for some astronomical objects.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] It is the altitude at which the FAI defines spaceflight to begin.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths between 100 and 1,000 kilometres (105 and 106 metres).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] A distance of 100 kilometres is approximately 62 miles (or 62.137 miles exactly).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *megametre* (SI symbol: *Mm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1000000 metres (106 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths starting at 106 m (1 Mm or 1,000 km).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths starting at 107 metres (10 megametres or 10,000 kilometres).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists lengths starting at 108 metres (100 megametres or 100,000 kilometres or 62,150 miles).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *gigametre* (SI symbol: *Gm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1000000000 metres (109 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths starting at 109 metres (1 gigametre (Gm) or 1 billion metres).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths starting at 1010 metres (10 gigametres (Gm) or 10 million kilometres, or 0.07 astronomical units).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare distances at different orders of magnitude this section lists lengths starting at 1011 metres (100 gigametre or 100 million kilometres or 0.7 astronomical units).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *terametre* (SI symbol: *Tm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1000000000000 metres (1012 m).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances, this section lists lengths starting at 1012 m (1 Tm or 1 billion km or 6.7 astronomical units).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths starting at 1013 m (10 Tm or 10 billion km or 67 astronomical units).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths starting at 1014 m (100 Tm or 100 billion km or 670 astronomical units).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *petametre* (SI symbol: *Pm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1015 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths starting at 1015 m (1 Pm or 1 trillion km or 6685 astronomical units (AU) or 0.11 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths starting at 1016 m (10 Pm or 66,800 AU, 1.06 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths between 1017 m (100 Pm or 11 light-years) and 1018 m (106 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *exametre* (SI symbol: *Em*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1018 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different distances this section lists lengths between 1018 m (1 Em or 105.7 light-years) and 1019 m (10 Em or 1,057 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 10 Em (1019 m or 1,100 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 100 Em (1020 m or 11,000 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *zettametre* (SI symbol: *Zm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1021 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 1 Zm (1021 m or 110,000 light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 10 Zm (1022 m or 1.1 million light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 100 Zm (1023 m or 11 million light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *yottametre* (SI symbol: *Ym*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1024 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 1 Ym (1024 m or 105.702 million light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 10 Ym (1025 m or 1.1 billion light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] At this scale, expansion of the universe becomes significant.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] Distance of these objects are derived from their measured redshifts, which depends on the cosmological models used.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 100 Ym (1026 m or 11 billion light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] Distance of these objects are derived from their measured redshifts, which depend on the cosmological models used.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *ronnametre* (SI symbol: *Rm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1027 metres.
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] To help compare different orders of magnitude, this section lists distances starting at 1 Rm (1027 m or 105.7 billion light-years).
[src:kilometre/attometre-p02] The *quettametre* (SI symbol: *Qm*) is a unit of length in the metric system equal to 1030 metres.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It is headquartered in the Pavillon de Breteuil in Saint-Cloud, near Paris, France.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The organisation has been referred to as **IBWM** (from its name in English) in older literature.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The BIPM has the mandate to provide the basis for a single, coherent system of measurements throughout the world, traceable to the International System of Units (SI).
[src:kilometre/bipm] This task takes many forms, from direct dissemination of units to coordination through international comparisons of national measurement standards (as in electricity and ionising radiation).
[src:kilometre/bipm] Following consultation, a draft version of the BIPM Work Programme is presented at each meeting of the General Conference for consideration with the BIPM budget.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The final programme of work is determined by the CIPM in accordance with the budget agreed to by the CGPM.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The BIPM is one of the twelve member organisations of the International Network on Quality Infrastructure (INetQI), which promotes and implements QI activities in metrology, accreditation, standardisation and conformity assessment.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The BIPM has an important role in maintaining accurate worldwide time of day.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It combines, analyses, and averages the official atomic time standards of member nations around the world to create a single, official Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:kilometre/bipm] These organs are also commonly referred to by their French initialisms.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The creation of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures followed the Metre Convention of 1875, after the Franco-Prussian War (1870–1871), at the initiative of the International Geodetic Association.
[src:kilometre/bipm] This process began with the 1855 Paris Exposition, shortly after the Great Exhibition, when the need for international standardisation of weights and measures became apparent.
[src:kilometre/bipm] During the process of unification of Germany, geodesists called for the establishment of an International Bureau of Weights and Measures in Europe.
[src:kilometre/bipm] These trends culminated in the 1889 General Conference on Weights and Measures, with the distribution of the metre and kilogram standards to the States parties to the Metre Convention.
[src:kilometre/bipm] When the metre was adopted as an international unit of length, it was well known that it no longer corresponded to its historical definition.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Carlos Ibáñez e Ibáñez de Ibero, first president of both the International Geodetic Association and the International Committee for Weigths and Measures, took part to the remeasurement and extension of the arc measurement of Delambre and Méchain.
[src:kilometre/bipm] At that time, mathematicians like Legendre and Gauss had developed new methods for processing data, including the least squares method which allowed to compare experimental data tainted with observational errors to a mathematical model.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In the 19th century, units of measurement were defined by primary standards, and unique artefacts made of different alloys with distinct coefficients of expansion were the legal basis of units of length.
[src:kilometre/bipm] A wrought iron ruler, the Toise of Peru, also called *Toise de l'Académie*, was the French primary standard of the toise, and the metre was officially defined by an artefact made of platinum kept in the National Archives.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Besides the latter, another platinum and twelve iron standards of the metre were made by Étienne Lenoir in 1799.
[src:kilometre/bipm] One of them became known as the Committee Meter in the United States and served as standard of length in the United States Coast Survey until 1890.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1855, the Dufour map (French: *Carte Dufour*), the first topographic map of Switzerland for which the metre was adopted as the unit of length, won the gold medal at the Exposition Universelle.
[src:kilometre/bipm] However, the baselines for this map were measured in 1834 with three toises long measuring rods calibrated on a toise made in 1821 by Jean Nicolas Fortin for Friedrich Georg Wilhelm von Struve.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The geodetic measuring device calibrated on the metre devised by Carlos Ibáñez e Ibáñez de Ibero and Frutos Saavedra Meneses, was displayed by Jean Brunner at the Exhibition.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In order to maintain measurement traceability it was important to control the temperature during these intercomparisons in order to avoid systematic errors.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The Earth measurements thus underscored the importance of scientific methods at a time when statistics were implemented in geodesy.
[src:kilometre/bipm] As a leading scientist of his time, Carlos Ibáñez e Ibáñez de Ibero was one of the 81 initial members of the International Statistical Institute (ISI) and delegate of Spain to the first ISI session (now called World Statistic Congress) in Rome in 1887.
[src:kilometre/bipm] On the sidelines of the Exposition Universelle (1855) and the second Congress of Statistics held in Paris, an association with a view to obtaining a uniform decimal system of measures, weights and currencies was created in 1855.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Under the impetus of this association, a Committee for Weights and Measures and Monies (French: *Comité des poids, mesures et monnaies*) would be created during the Exposition Universelle (1867) in Paris and would call for the international adoption of the metric system.
[src:kilometre/bipm] At the 1867 Universal Exposition in Paris, the Netherland, Switzerland, Russia, the United States and Spain were respectively represented by Edouard Henri von Baumhauer, Carl Feer-Herzog, Moritz von Jacobi, Samuel B.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Ruggles, and Ramón de la Sagra on the Weights and Measures and Currency Committee of the Association for the Promotion of the Metric System, which was presided by Claude-Louis Mathieu, with Edmond Becquerel as vice-president, Leone Levi and Henri Baudrillart as secretaries.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1858, a Technical Commission was set up to continue cadastral surveying inaugurated under Muhammad Ali.
[src:kilometre/bipm] This Commission suggested to buy geodetic devices which were ordered in France.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Mohammed Sa'id Pasha entrusted to Ismail Mustafa al-Falaki the study of the precision apparatus calibrated against the metre intended to measure geodetic baselines and built by Jean Brunner in Paris.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Ismail Mustafa had the task to carry out the experiments necessary for determining the expansion coefficients of the two platinum and brass bars, and to compare the Egyptian standard with a known standard.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The Spanish standard designed by Carlos Ibáñez e Ibáñez de Ibero and Frutos Saavedra Meneses was chosen for this purpose, as it had served as a model for the construction of the Egyptian standard.
[src:kilometre/bipm] A French scientific instrument maker, Jean Nicolas Fortin, made three direct copies of the Toise of Peru, one for Friedrich Georg Wilhelm von Struve, a second for Heinrich Christian Schumacher in 1821 and a third for Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel in 1823.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1831, Henri-Prudence Gambey also realised a copy of the Toise of Peru which was kept at Altona Observatory in Hamburg.
[src:kilometre/bipm] According to geodesists, these standards were secondary standards deduced from the Toise of Peru.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In continental Europe, except Spain, surveyors continued to use measuring instruments calibrated on the Toise of Peru.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Among these, the toise of Bessel and the apparatus of Borda were respectively the main references for geodesy in Prussia and in France.
[src:kilometre/bipm] These measuring devices consisted of bimetallic rulers in platinum and brass or iron and zinc fixed together at one extremity to assess the variations in length produced by any change in temperature.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The combination of two bars made of two different metals allowed to take thermal expansion into account without measuring the temperature.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The Spanish Standard, which would be retained as the fundamental standard of the metre in Spain until the reception of the international prototypes of the metre, was itself calibrated on the Borda Toise.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Not, as it was mistakenly assumed for a certain time, that the Association had the unscientific thought of modifying the length of the metre, in order to conform exactly to its historical definition according to the new values that would be found for the terrestrial meridian.
[src:kilometre/bipm] But, busy combining the arcs measured in the different countries and connecting the neighbouring triangulations, geodesists encountered, as one of the main difficulties, the unfortunate uncertainty which reigned over the equations of the units of length used.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1867 at the second General Conference of the International Association of Geodesy held in Berlin, the question of an international standard unit of length was discussed in order to combine the measurements made in different countries to determine the size and shape of the Earth.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler's metrological and geodetic work also had a favourable response in Russia.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Heinrich von Wild is another example illustrating the role played by Swiss scientists in the creation of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The Swiss physicist and meteorologist was delegated by Russia to the International Metre Commission in 1870, to the Diplomatic Conference of 1875, and, after the signing of the Metre Convention, to the International Committee for Weights and Measures.
[src:kilometre/bipm] He was director of the Swiss Federal Institute of Metrology (METAS) since 1864.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1879, he would become the first president of the International Meteorological Organization.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The French Academy of Sciences and the Bureau des Longitudes in Paris drew the attention of the French government to this issue.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In November 1869, Napoleon III issued invitations to join the International Metre Commission.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The French government gave practical support to the creation of an International Metre Commission, which met in Paris in 1870 and again in 1872 with the participation of about thirty countries.
[src:kilometre/bipm] There was much discussion within this commission, considering the opportunity either to keep as definitive the units represented by the standards of the Archives, or to return to the primitive definitions, and to correct the units to bring them closer to them.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Since its origin, the metre has kept a double definition; it is both the ten-millionth part of the quarter meridian and the length represented by the *Mètre des Archives*.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The first is historical, the second is metrological.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The first solution prevailed, in accordance with common sense and in accordance with the advice of the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Abandoning the values represented by the standards, would have consecrated an extremely dangerous principle, that of the change of units to any progress of measurements; the Metric System would be perpetually threatened with change, that is to say with ruin.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Thus the Commission called for the creation of a new international prototype metre which length would be as close as possible to that of the *Mètre des Archives* and the arrangement of a system where national standards could be compared with it.
[src:kilometre/bipm] At the session on 12 October 1872 of the Permanent Committee of the International Metre Commission, which was to become the International Committee for Weights and Measures, Carlos Ibáñez e Ibáñez de Ibero was elected president.
[src:kilometre/bipm] On 19 April 1875, Ibáñez' presidency was confirmed and Adolphe Hirsch was elected secretary of the International Committee for Weights and Measures.
[src:kilometre/bipm] On 6 May 1873 during the 6th session of the French section of the Metre Commission, Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville cast a 20-kilogram platinum-iridium ingot from Matthey in his laboratory at the École normale supérieure (Paris).
[src:kilometre/bipm] On 13 May 1874, 250 kilograms of platinum-iridium to be used for several national prototypes of the metre was cast at the Conservatoire national des arts et métiers.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In fact, the chemical analysis of the alloy produced in 1874 by the French section revealed contamination by ruthenium and iron which led the International Committee for Weights and Measures to reject, in 1877, the prototypes produced by the French section from the 1874 alloy.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It also seemed at the time that the production of prototypes with an X profile was only possible through the extrusion process, which resulted in iron contamination.
[src:kilometre/bipm] However, it soon turned out that the prototypes designed by Henri Tresca could be produced by milling.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The principal tasks facing the delegates at the 1875 conference was the replacement of the existing metre and kilogram artefacts that were held by the French Government and the setting up of an organisation to administer the maintenance of standards around the globe.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The conference did not concern itself with other units of measure.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The conference had undertones of Franco-German political manoeuvring, particularly since the French had been humiliated by the Prussians during the war a few years previously.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Although France lost control of the metric system, they ensured that it passed to international rather than German control and that the international headquarters were in Paris.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The first advocated for the creation of an International Bureau of Weights and Measures in France.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The second favored maintaining the status quo in favor of the National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts (CNAM).
[src:kilometre/bipm] The French delegation itself appeared divided between the Republic's position, which supported the creation of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures, and the French Conservatory, represented by Arthur Morin.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Initially, France adopted an officially neutral position, while allowing General Morin to secretly lobby foreign delegations in the Conservatory's interest.
[src:kilometre/bipm] A third option was considered: the creation of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures in Switzerland.
[src:kilometre/bipm] This option seemed unlikely to succeed from the outset due to the strong support from Spain and Italy for the creation of the International Bureau in Paris.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Following an ultimatum from Wilhelm Foerster, the German delegate, the French delegation officially declared its support for the creation of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The Metre Convention was signed on 20 May 1875 in Paris and the International Bureau of Weights and Measures was created under the supervision of the International Committee for Weights and Measures, presided by Carlos Ibáñez e ibáñez de Ibero.
[src:kilometre/bipm] We know that the *Mètre des Archives* is about one-fifth of a millimeter too short compared to its 1791 definition—that is, compared to the true pole-equator distance—but this fact did not trigger the movement that led to a new definition of the metre.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Rather, the metrological quality of geodetic standards calibrated on the Toise of Peru was gradually proving insufficient to meet the growing need for accuracy in geodetic measurements.
[src:kilometre/bipm] From geodesists point of view, the *Mètre des Archives* was a secondary standard deduced from the Toise of Peru.
[src:kilometre/bipm] When, in 1799, the results necessary for the practical and definitive realization of the metre were available, the commission in charge of the matter decided to fully utilize the precision of the comparator developed by the engineer Étienne Lenoir.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It fixed the length of the definitive metre at 3 feet 11.296 lines (or 443.296 lines).
[src:kilometre/bipm] The law of 18 Germinal, Year III (April 7, 1795) stipulated that the metre should be drawn on a platinum ruler.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Lenoir therefore constructed the prototype of the standard metre according to these criteria.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Another platinum standard, as well as twelve other iron standards, were also produced in 1799.
[src:kilometre/bipm] At the first general meeting of the Central European Arc Measurement held in Berlin in 1864, it was decided to adopt the Bessel Toise, a copy of the Toise of Peru made in 1923 by Jean-Nicolas Fortin in Paris, as the international standard.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In order to avoid the difficulty in exactly determining the temperature of a bar by the mercury thermometer, Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel, inspired by Jean-Charles de Borda, introduced in 1834 near Königsberg a compound bar which constituted a metallic thermometer.
[src:kilometre/bipm] A zinc bar was laid on an iron bar two toises long, both bars being perfectly planed and in free contact, the zinc bar being slightly shorter and the two bars rigidly united at one end.
[src:kilometre/bipm] As the temperature varied, the difference of the lengths of the bars, as perceived by the other end, also varied, and afforded a quantitative correction for temperature variations, which was applied to reduce the length to standard temperature.
[src:kilometre/bipm] During the measurement of the base line the bars were not allowed to come into contact, the interval being measured by the insertion of glass wedges.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The results of the comparisons of four measuring rods with one another and with the standards were elaborately computed by the method of least-squares.These comparisons were essential.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Indeed, thermal expansion, which corresponds to the increase in volume of a body caused by heating, was already well known at the time.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Pierre Bouguer had demonstrated it to a large audience at the Hôtel des Invalides.
[src:kilometre/bipm] This problem has consistently dominated all thinking regarding the measurement of geodetic standards.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Geodesists were preoccupied with the constant concern of accurately determining the temperature of the length standards used in the field.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Determining this variable, on which the length of measuring instruments depends, has always been considered so complex and so important that one could almost say that the history of geodetic standards corresponds to the history of the precautions taken to avoid temperature errors.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In the 19th century, statisticians knew that scientific observations were subject to two types of error: constant errors and random errors.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The effects of the latter could be corrected using the least squares method.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Constant errors, on the other hand, had to be carefully avoided, as they were caused by various factors that consistently altered the results of observations in the same direction.
[src:kilometre/bipm] These errors thus tended to render the results they affected worthless.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Consider, for example, measuring a straight line to determine its length in metres.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In the absence of a standard temperature scale, inconsistencies arose when attempting to link geodetic surveys from different countries to create a European geodetic network.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It was thus crucial to compare at controlled temperatures with great precision and to the same unit all the standards for measuring geodetic baselines.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The result of these comparisons made it possible to reduce the arcs measured in Germany to the metre.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The discordance of ⁠1/66 000⁠ which remained between the triangles common to the German and French networks could be reduced to ⁠1/600 000⁠ which was at the limit of accuracy of geodetic surveys at the time.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In fact, the length of Bessel's Toise, which according to the then legal ratio between the metre and the Toise of Peru, should be equal to 1.9490348 m, would be found to be 26.2·10−6 m greater during measurements carried out by Jean-René Benoît at the BIPM.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Careful comparisons with several standard toises showed that the international metre calibrated on the *Mètre des Archives* was not exactly equal to the legal metre or 443.296 lines of the toise, but, in round numbers, ⁠1/75 000⁠ of the length smaller, or approximately 0.013 millimetres.
[src:kilometre/bipm] By contrast, in 2007, a comparison of the American Committee meter and its Swiss counterpart was carried out at NIST and METAS.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The two metre standards can be considered perfectly equivalent, with a difference of only (0.96 ±3.0) micrometres.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The poor quality of the measuring surfaces explained the significant uncertainty in the measurements compared to today's standards.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In his 2002 book *The measure of all things*, Ken Alder recalled that the legal metre is about 0.2 millimetres shorter than it should be according to its original proposed definition.
[src:kilometre/bipm] However, the error in measuring the length of Paris meridian represented less than 2% of the total error, and the error due to a flawed assumption about the shape of the Earth contributed to approximately 3% of the total error.
[src:kilometre/bipm] If the meticulous work of Pierre Méchain and Jean Baptiste Delambre were the only source of error, the current metre would be too long by less than 4 μm instead of being too short by 197 μm.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The 95% of the missing length of the legal metre is due to the failure to account for vertical deflections; this was beyond the scope of Delambre and Méchain because the Earth's gravitational field had not yet been studied.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The progresses of metrology combined with those of gravimetry through gravimeters with variant of Repsold-Bessel pendulum led to a new era of geodesy.
[src:kilometre/bipm] If precision metrology had needed the help of geodesy, it could not continue to prosper without the help of metrology.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It was then necessary to define a single unit to express all the measurements of terrestrial arcs, and all determinations of the gravitational acceleration by the means of pendulum.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The 1875 Conference of the International Association of Geodesy also dealt with the best instrument to be used for the determination of gravitational acceleration.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1901, Friedrich Robert Helmert found, mainly by gravimetry, parameters of the ellipsoid remarkably close to reality.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Although marked by the concern to correct vertical deflections, taking into account the contributions of gravimetry, research between 1910 and 1950 remained practically limited to large continental triangulations.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The most significant work would be that by John Fillmore Hayford, which relied mainly on the North American national network.
[src:kilometre/bipm] His ellipsoid was adopted in 1924 by the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1889, the General Conference on Weights and Measures, presided by Alfred Descloizeaux, met at the Pavillon de Breteuil, the seat of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Thus, the Contracting States also received a collection of thermometers whose accuracy made it possible to ensure that of length measurements.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The international prototype metre would also be a "line standard"; that is, the metre was defined as the distance between two lines marked on the bar, so avoiding the wear problems of end standards.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The foundation of the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey by Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler paved the way to the actual definition of the metre, with Charles Sanders Peirce being the first to experimentally link the metre to the wavelength of a spectral line.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Albert Abraham Michelson soon took up the idea and improved it.
[src:kilometre/bipm] On the other hand, the comparison of the new prototypes of the metre with each other involved the development of special measuring equipment and the definition of a reproducible temperature scale.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Guillaume's Nobel Prize marked the end of an era in which metrology was leaving the field of geodesy to become an autonomous scientific discipline able of redefining the metre through technological applications of physics.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1906, before the opening of the Simplon Tunnel, Swiss surveyors measured the distance between the stations of Iselle di Trasquera and Brig, Switzerland using invar wire instruments.
[src:kilometre/bipm] This method was subsequently used in the construction of large particle accelerators.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1987 the International Bureau of Weights and Measures took over some of the work of the International Time Bureau when it was dissolved in 1987.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The remaining tasks were assigned to the International Earth Rotation and Reference Systems Service (IERS), which replaced the International Polar Motion Service and the earth-rotation section of the International Time Bureau.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Already in 1936, irregularities in the speed of Earth's rotation due to the unpredictable movement of air and water masses were discovered through the use of quartz clocks.
[src:kilometre/bipm] They implied that the Earth's rotation was an imprecise way of determining time.
[src:kilometre/bipm] In 1967, the second was redefined based on atomic clocks, resulting in the International Atomic Time (TAI).
[src:kilometre/bipm] The International Bureau of Weights and Measures began to establish atomic clocks world-wide, numbering more than 450 currently.
[src:kilometre/bipm] The International System of Units (SI, abbreviated from the French *Système international (d'unités)*), the modern form of the metric system was revised in 2019.
[src:kilometre/bipm] It is the only system of measurement with an official status in nearly every country in the world.
[src:kilometre/bipm] Since 2019, the magnitudes of all SI units have been defined by declaring exact numerical values for seven *defining constants* when expressed in terms of their SI units.
[src:kilometre/bipm] These defining constants are the hyperfine transition frequency of caesium Δ*ν*Cs, the speed of light in vacuum *c*, the Planck constant *h*, the elementary charge *e*, the Boltzmann constant *k*, the Avogadro constant *N*A, and the luminous efficacy *K*cd.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] A **centimetre** (International spelling) or **centimeter** (American English), with SI symbol **cm**, is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI) equal to one hundredth of a metre, *centi-* being the SI prefix for a factor of ⁠1/100⁠.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] Equivalently, there are 100 centimetres in 1 metre.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] The centimetre is the base unit of length in the now deprecated centimetre–gram–second (CGS) system of units.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] Though for many physical quantities, SI prefixes for factors of 103—like *milli-* and *kilo-*—are often preferred by technicians, the centimetre remains a practical unit of length for many everyday measurements; for instance, human height is commonly measured in centimetres.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] A centimetre is approximately the width of the fingernail of an average adult person.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] One millilitre is defined as one cubic centimetre, under the SI system of units.
[src:kilometre/centimetre] These characters are each equal in size to one Chinese character and are typically used only with East Asian, fixed-width CJK fonts.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He did undergraduate school at the University of Wisconsin in Madison with meteorology as his major and obtained his B.Sc. in the spring of 1967.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Doswell continued at the University of Oklahoma (OU), finishing a M.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Doswell was called for military service in August 1969 and after basic training was assigned to the Atmospheric Sciences Laboratory at White Sands Missile Range, in New Mexico, for a study on fog modeling.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] In 1972, he resumed graduate studies at OU, where he got a PhD in Meteorology in 1976.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Having worked summers as a student at the National Severe Storms Forecast Center (NSSFC is now the Storm Prediction Center), in Kansas City, Missouri, Doswell was hired as a Research Forecaster at the Techniques Development Unit (TDU) of NSSFC.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] In 1982, he went to the Environmental Research Laboratories (ERL) Weather Research Program (WRP) in Boulder, Colorado, and then to the National Severe Storms Laboratory (NSSL) in Norman, Oklahoma in 1986.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He retired from federal service in 2001 at which time joined the Cooperative Institute for Mesoscale Meteorological Studies (CIMMS) at the University of Oklahoma where he also continued to teach part-time.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He was a lead forecaster for the first project VORTEX in 1994/1995, produced more than 100 refereed publications, and several contributions to books and encyclopedias.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He edited the American Meteorological Society (AMS) monograph *Severe Convective Storms* as well as co-authored two papers there.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Doswell was among the first scientific storm chasers, and continued to chase recreationally later in life.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He was a semi-professional photographer, with a special emphasis on storm photographs and also was a Certified Consulting Meteorologist (CCM).
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] His professional storm chasing also included being a storm intercept tour guide as an expert lecturer.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He spoke several times annually across the country, and occasionally internationally, to lay crowds to storm spotter seminars to storm chaser conventions to scientific conferences.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Doswell appeared in *The Chasers of Tornado Alley* (1996) along with friend and meteorologist Alan Moller.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] The award-winning documentary film about storm chasing, produced and directed by storm chaser and filmmaker Martin Lisius, follows Doswell and Moller as they intercept a powerful tornado in the small town of Pampa, Texas, on June 8, 1995.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Doswell captured significant, up-close footage of the tornado which appeared in the film.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] His video of this tornado as well as other storm photos and videos appeared in several television shows and documentaries.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He also contributed to storm spotter training materials and studied spotter history and instruction techniques.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] He hosted the blues program *Juke Joint* and co-hosted, with Gene Rhoden and RJ Evans, a talk show program about severe storms, *High Instability*, both on the ShockNet internet radio station.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] Dowswell died on January 18, 2025, at age 79, in Norman, Oklahoma.
[src:kilometre/charles-a-doswell-iii] A memorial service was held at the National Weather Center (NWC).
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The **kilometre** (SI symbol: **km**; /ˈkɪləmiːtər/ or /kɪˈlɒmətər/), spelt **kilometer** in American English, is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI), equal to one thousand metres (kilo- being the SI prefix for 1000).
[src:kilometre/kilometre] It is the preferred measurement unit to express distances between geographical places on land in most of the world; notable exceptions are the United States, the United Kingdom, and Liberia where the statute mile is used.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] There are two common pronunciations for the word.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] It is generally preferred by the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC), the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC), and the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC).
[src:kilometre/kilometre] Many other users, particularly in countries where SI (the metric system) is not widely used, use the second pronunciation with stress on the second syllable.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The second pronunciation follows the stress pattern used for the names of measuring instruments (such as *micrometer*, *barometer*, *thermometer*, *tachometer,* and *speedometer*).
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The contrast is even more obvious in countries that use the American spelling of the word *metre*.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] This pronunciation is irregular because it makes the kilometre the only SI unit with the stress on the second syllable.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] After Australia introduced the metric system in 1970, the first pronunciation was declared official by the government's Metric Conversion Board.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] However, the Australian prime minister at the time, Gough Whitlam, insisted that the second pronunciation was the correct one because of the Greek origins of the two parts of the word.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] By a decree on 8 May 1790, the French National Constituent Assembly ordered the French Academy of Sciences to develop a new measurement system.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] In August 1793, the French National Convention decreed the metre as the sole length measurement system in the French Republic and it was based on ⁠1/10⁠ millionth of the distance from the orbital poles (either North or South) to the Equator, this being a truly internationally based unit.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The first name of the kilometre was "Millaire".
[src:kilometre/kilometre] Although the metre was formally defined in 1799, the myriametre (10000 metres) was preferred to the "kilometre" for everyday use.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The term "*myriamètre*" appeared a number of times in the text of Develey's book *Physique d'Emile: ou, Principes de la science de la nature*, (published in 1802), while the term *kilometre* only appeared in an appendix.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] French maps published in 1835 had scales showing *myriametres* and "*lieues de Poste*" (Postal leagues of about 4288 metres).
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The Dutch, on the other hand, adopted the kilometre in 1817 but gave it the local name of the *mijl*.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] It was only in 1867 that the term "*kilometer*" became the only official unit of measure in the Netherlands to represent 1000 metres.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] Two German textbooks dated 1842 and 1848 respectively give a snapshot of the use of the kilometre across Europe: the kilometre was in use in the Netherlands and in Italy, and the myriametre was in use in France.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] In 1935, the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) officially abolished the prefix "myria-" and with it the "myriametre", leaving the kilometre as the recognised unit of length for measurements of that magnitude.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] The symbol **km** for the kilometre is in lower case and has been standardised by the BIPM.
[src:kilometre/kilometre] A slang term for the kilometre in the US, UK, and Canadian militaries is *klick*.
